      <p>When a payroll deadline slips, two different jobs run in parallel. The licensed job &mdash; filing the late 941/940 or state return, calculating and addressing penalties and interest, requesting abatement or a payment arrangement, and representing the business before the IRS or a state agency &mdash; belongs to your CPA, enrolled agent, or tax attorney. A bookkeeping firm cannot do that work, and we don&rsquo;t. The operational job is getting the payroll books accurate and current so the licensed professional can act fast: reconciling the payroll liability and bank accounts, confirming wage and withholding figures tie out, recovering any periods the books fell behind, and assembling the documented numbers the filing needs. A Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor does that against a written scope. Independent firm &mdash; not the IRS, not your CPA, not Intuit, and not Intuit&rsquo;s software support. Educational only; not legal or tax advice.</p>
